  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Emergency Nutrition and IYCF Support to the IDP and Drought Affected Communities of Borena and West Wollega Zones in Oromia and Wag Himra Zone in Amhara Region</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This emergency life-saving interventions targets three zones, namely Borena (Oromia), Wollega (Oromia) and Wag Himra (Amhara), providing emergency nutritional and care practices services to the most vulnerable population. All the three targeted zones has high level of emergency needs, with vulnerable women, men, boys and girls affected by acute malnutrition and poor access and availability of services. In Borena, frequent violence and resurgent displacements of populations affecting the already fragile health system. In West Wollega, violence following the September 2018 incident displaced around 70,000 persons into West Wollega. The additional population is putting strain on the previously fully functioning health system. Wag Himra zone is not affected by violence or IDPs, however high rates of undernutrition affects the population with limited access and utilization of health services due to challenging terrain affects the population and health system. For each area of intervention, AAH adapts their approach to reduce morbidity and mortality associated with under nutrition among children U5 and PLW. The project will  strengthen and sustain the existing health system, provide support for IDPs and Host Communities
reaching 99,607 beneficiaries (114 Men, 26,484 women, 35,850 boys and 37,159 girls). Some of the services provided through this action includes: treatment of Severe Acute Malnutrition (SAM) treatment of Moderate Acute Malnutrition (MAM) and Community Mobilisation Support to GoE outreach clinics where needed Promotion of Care Practices among children and their care-givers and psychosocial support for IDPs and host communities.</narrative>
  </description>
